               <msContents class="#STM">
                  <summary><p>
  The <title xml:lang="sa">Śisúpālavadha</title>, an ornate <term xml:lang="sa">kāvya</term> in 20 <term xml:lang="sa">sarga</term>s telling the story of the slaying of <term>Śiśupāla</term>, attracted many commentaries — likely due to its complexity — of which <persName xml:lang="sa">Mallinātha</persName>'s is the most well-attested in manuscripts. This manuscript contains <persName xml:lang="sa">Mallinātha</persName>'s commentary, called the <title xml:lang="sa">Sarvaṃkaṣā</title>, on verses 1–34 of the first <term xml:lang="sa">sarga</term> of the <title xml:lang="sa">Śiśupālavadha</title>.
</p>
<p>
  The 13 folios of this text is preceded and followed by many additional folios, written by a different hand. A note (not seen in the microfilm, and perhaps made later) identifies this as part IV of V parts, although it miscounts it as containing 14 folios.
</p>
<p>
  The microfilm images are illegible and displayed upside-down.
</p></summary>
                  
